==English==

===Etymology===
From the color of dress shirts worn by professional and clerical workers, as opposed to the rugged denim and chambray shirts normally worn by manual workers.

===Adjective===
'''[[white]]-[[collar]]'''

# Engaged or trained in or designated of office labor, as opposed to factory, industrial, or other essentially manual labor.  Professional or clerical class.
#:'''''White-collar''' workers represent an augmenting segment of society.''
# {{rfd-redundant}} Of or relating to persons who work in an office, as opposed to [[blue-collar]].  
# {{rfv-sense}} Pertaining to the culture of white-collar workers.
#: ''White-collar value can keep marriages together.''

